<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>"If We Must Die" by Claude McKay was significant because it:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Promoted racial reconciliation</option>
            <option letter="b">Called for dignified resistance against racial violence</option>
            <option letter="c">Supported segregation policies</option>
            <option letter="d">Described rural African American life</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Claude McKay's 1919 sonnet "If We Must Die" was a powerful call for African Americans to resist racial violence with dignity and courage. Written during the "Red Summer" of 1919, when racial violence swept across numerous American cities, the poem became an anthem of resistance against oppression. Its militant tone and classical form demonstrated both the political and artistic achievements of the Harlem Renaissance.</explanation>
    </question>
